<HEADLINE>
<P>
A QUICK STUDY, MEDEARIS PACES 5 AREA MASTERS' CHAMPIONS; HIGH SCHOOL TRACK AND 
FIELD: HART HIGH SENIOR BREAKS FAST AND IS NOT HEADED IN HIGH HURDLES. FISCHER 
SQUEAKS OUT WIN IN HIGH JUMP. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN ORTEGA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 He has been described by his coach as a student of hurdling. Apparently so. 
</P>
<P>
 Jason Medearis of Hart High learned from a week-old mistake and won the boys' 
110-meter high hurdles in the Southern Section Masters Meet at Cerritos College 
on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
 Medearis finished a disappointing third in the highs in the Division I 
championships at Long Beach Veterans Stadium last week. His miscue in that 
outing was breaking from the blocks slowly and then compounding his error by 
paying too much attention to rivals Kenny Haslip of Pasadena Muir and Tyson 
Murphy of Santa Monica. 
</P>
<P>
 This time, he shot out of the blocks and never looked back, recording a time 
of 14.21 seconds and defeating Division I champion Haslip (14.34) for the 
second time in seven meetings this season. 
</P>
<P>
 "I had a real good feeling because I didn't see anyone on either side of me at 
the start of the race," Medearis said. "And that acted as motivation to keep it 
that way for the rest of the race." 
</P>
<P>
 Although Haslip bounced back to defeat Medearis in the 300 intermediate 
hurdles, 36.65 to 36.80, the Hart senior couldn't complain about his time. It 
was a personal best by more than half a second and moved him into third on the 
yearly national high school list behind Lee Hutton (36.5) of La Marque (Tex.) 
High and Haslip. 
</P>
<P>
 It was also the fastest time by an athlete from the region since 1976, when 
Charles White of San Fernando timed 36.4 to win the 330-yard intermediates in 
the now-defunct International Prep Invitational. 
</P>
<P>
 "Last week definitely helped me tonight," Medearis said. "It made me think 
more this week about what I had to do, about what I wanted to accomplish." 
</P>
<P>
 Medearis was among five athletes from the region who posted victories in the 
meet in which the top five finishers in each event qualified for the state 
championships at Cerritos, June 3-4. 
</P>
<P>
 The others were Jeremy Fischer of Camarillo in the high jump, Esa Sallinen of 
Burroughs in the pole vault, Jamaal Chase of Quartz Hill in the triple jump and 
Dolores Tuimoloau of Channel Islands in the girls' shotput. 
</P>
<P>
 Fischer and Arthur Lloyd of Rialto Eisenhower each cleared seven feet in the 
high jump, but Fischer won because he cleared the height on his second attempt 
while Lloyd needed three tries. 
</P>
<P>
 Fischer also finished third in the long jump at 22-9 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
 Sallinen, a senior exchange student from Finland, cleared 16 feet on his 
second attempt in the pole vault before missing three times at 16-6. 
</P>
<P>
 Chase was a double qualifier, finishing second in the long jump (22-10 1/4) 
and winning the triple jump at 48-10 3/4, his best outdoor mark of the season. 
</P>
<P>
 Tuimoloau, the state leader in the girls' shotput at 49-2, won that event with 
a mark of 45-1 3/4. She also placed fourth in the discus at 137-1. 
</P>
<P>
 Tuimoloau and Palmdale sophomore Kristi Rose both produced clutch throws on 
their final attempts in the discus to advance to the state meet. 
</P>
<P>
 Rose was last in the field of nine after the three of the four rounds, but she 
threw a personal best of 135-10 on her final effort to temporarily move into 
fourth and push Tuimoloau (131-11) into sixth. 
</P>
<P>
 Unfazed, Tuimoloau calmly stepped in the ring and unleashed an even better 
throw. 
</P>
<P>
 In other events, Brett Strahan of Hart, Antonio Arce of Palmdale, Kim 
Mortensen of Thousand Oaks, Cathy Prater of Agoura and Liz Giltner of Chaminade 
placed second in their respective events. 
</P>
<P>
 Chase leaped 22-10 1/4 to finish second in the long jump before winning the 
triple jump at 48-10 3/4, his best outdoor mark of the season. 
</P>
<P>
 Strahan ran 4 minutes 14.70 seconds to finish behind Eric Dunn (4:14.47) of 
Arroyo Grande in the 1,600. Arce timed a yearly region-leading time of 9:09.21 
in the 3,200 to finish behind Jaime Martinez (9:06.08) of Orange. 
</P>
<P>
 Mortensen ran a region-leading 10:53.65 in the girls' 3,200; Prater ran the 
second fastest time (43.96) of her career in the 300 low hurdles; and freshman 
Giltner cleared a personal best of 5-8 in the high jump. 
</P>
<P>
 Jessica De La Cerda of Hart was a notable non-qualifier. She placed ninth in 
the girls' 1,600 with a time of 5:47.00. 
</P>
</TEXT>
