<TEXT>
<P>
 Administration Drops Bank Regulatory Reform: The Clinton Administration has 
abandoned plans to pass legislation this year consolidating bank regulation, 
the Treasury Department said.A Treasury official who insisted on anonymity said 
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen decided to shelve the proposal after failing to reach 
agreement on a compromise with Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan. 
The Administration has proposed merging all four bank regulatory agencies into 
a Federal Banking Commission. The four agencies are the Comptroller of the 
Currency, the Office of Thrift Supervision, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
and the Federal Reserve System. The Federal Reserve Board, which would be 
stripped of its power to regulate banks, has opposed the bill. 
</P>
