<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FOUNTAIN VALLEY; MAN SENTENCED TO DIE IN 1989 MURDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RENE LYNCH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 33-year-old Missouri man with a history of sexual assaults was sentenced to 
die Friday for the murder and attempted rape of a Fountain Valley mother who 
was on her way home to breast-feed her infant daughter. 
</P>
<P>
 The judge told Timothy DePriest that the December, 1989, slaying of Hong Thi 
Nguyen, 26, was so cruel and vicious that the defendant deserved no mercy. 
</P>
<P>
 "The aggravating evidence is simply overwhelming," said Orange County Superior 
Court Judge Everett W. Dickey. 
</P>
<P>
 "She was strangled, shot, treated very brutally for no reason that I can see . 
. . treated as though she were a piece of garbage," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Tuyen Ngo, the victim's husband, said he attended the sentencing hearing 
because he wanted to be sure that DePriest received the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
 DePriest is the 29th person sentenced to death row from Orange County. He also 
faces a life sentence plus 57 years in his home state, where he was convicted 
of sexually assaulting a woman and shooting a police officer. 
</P>
<P>
 At the time of the murder, DePriest was on parole for a rape conviction in San 
Bernardino County. He had been charged in a second rape in San Bernardino, but 
in a plea agreement with prosecutors only admitted to a robbery. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Public Defender William G. Kelley said he believes his client's life 
should have been spared, in part, because DePriest is the product of an 
abusive, dysfunctional family. 
</P>
<P>
 But prosecutor Christopher J. Evans said Dist. Atty. Michael R. Capizzi 
insisted the case be pursued as a death penalty matter because of the cruelty 
involved. RENE LYNCH 
</P>
</TEXT>
