<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: GRANADA HILLS; 2 HORSE BOARDERS FACE LOSS OF PERMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM CROGAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles City Planning Commission's Office of Zoning Administration on 
Friday ordered two commercial horse-boarding businesses to comply with Building 
and Safety Department standards within 90 days or lose their permits. 
</P>
<P>
 "Normally, these kinds of actions are only taken in very serious cases, like 
motels where prostitution or illegal drug sales are occurring," said Joe 
Perica, associate zoning administrator. "This was just our way of getting these 
people's attention and telling them that the clock was striking midnight on 
these violations." 
</P>
<P>
 At issue were longstanding failures by Hillcrest Ranch, on Zelzah Avenue, and 
Damoor Farms, on Rinaldi Street, to comply with several requirements attached 
to their permits to operate. Both are in Granada Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 Hillcrest Ranch, which now boards 35 horses, is owned and operated by Shari 
Steinberg. Its permit, issued in 1989, came with the proviso that Steinberg 
obtain all necessary county health permits and building and safety permits for 
exiting structures, set aside on-site parking for 10 cars, control dust and 
store horse manure in covered containers.  
</P>
<P>
 She also agreed to build a bridle path and improve the road on the part of 
Zelzah that fronts her property.  
</P>
<P>
 Damoor Farms, operated by Roland Davis and his daughter, Michelle Valentine, 
received a permit in 1986. In 1991, they were reported in violation of city 
codes for failing to obtain permits for existing and new structures, to correct 
electrical and plumbing problems and for the storage of an unlicensed motor 
home on the property.  
</P>
<P>
 Building and Safety Investigator Galyn Taylor said Friday that both sets of 
owners had now made substantial progress toward compliance. 
</P>
<P>
 Under a compromise, Steinberg agreed to grade and improve her road, build a 
bridle path and complete the permit process on her buildings. 
</P>
<P>
 Davis and Valentine agreed to obtain permits and complete repairs on all 
existing buildings, replace their motor home with a newer model and complete 
electrical repairs. JIM CROGAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
